## Owning a 2010 Land Rover Discovery 4 (LR4): A 4.5-Year Repair Overview

*A DIY owner documents every major failure and repair on a V6 diesel Discovery 4 over four and a half years, revealing the true cost and effort of keeping an aging Land Rover on the road.*

---

### 🚗 The Vehicle

- **Spec**: 2010 Land Rover Discovery 4 (LR4), **3.0L V6 diesel**, SE trim (Australia) — no electric seats, no leather, but includes 7 seats and rear A/C
- **Aftermarket upgrade**: Added a **Carpuride W901** Android Auto/Apple CarPlay head unit with a custom flip-up bracket to retain access to the original display menus
- **Purchase price**: ~**AUD $35,000**; current estimated value: ~**AUD $17,000** — a ~**$18,000 depreciation** in 4.5 years

---

### 🔧 Major Repairs Completed

- **Air suspension pump failure**: Pump wasn't generating enough pressure to raise the car, confirmed using a **GAP2 diagnostic tool**; replacement was straightforward on a hoist but involves one awkward bolt
- **Alternator replacement**: Buried low in the engine bay with a power wire too short to work comfortably; was triggering a charge error despite a new battery — described as "a swine to do"
- **Cracked throttle body**: Crack was hidden underneath and only revealed by a **smoke test**; genuine Land Rover replacement cost **AUD $1,200** (aftermarket equivalent ~**$300**) — owner acknowledges aftermarket would likely have sufficed
- **Front left air shock replacement**: Airbag leak visible only at full suspension height; replaced both front units; main challenge was insufficient spare hose length for easy reconnection
- **Oil cooler replacement**: Located deep in the **V of the engine**; the factory-approved removal method proved impossible in practice due to a blocking bracket — owner cut the bracket off to extract it, noting it's a Discovery 3 legacy bracket largely redundant on the Disco 4
- **Cracked inlet manifold (left side)**: Discovered shortly after the oil cooler job — would have been far easier to tackle simultaneously; left side is harder due to a bolt hidden behind the timing cover; job took **~10 hours**

---

### ⚠️ Current Known Issues & Planned Fixes

- **Intermittent A/C**: Suspected faulty **solenoid valve**; replacement part already sourced; plans to drain and refill with **HyChill 30** refrigerant (a DIY-compatible gas) instead of standard refrigerant
- **Cracked rear high-mount stop light**: Heavy rain caused interior flooding; AliExpress replacement part sourced; unit is glued in — plans to reseal with **Sikaflex 258** primeless windscreen adhesive
- **Saggy headlining**: Temporarily held up with fabric pigtail pins; full repair undecided
- **Both rear door locks intermittent**: Parts sourced; repair planned and will be filmed
- **Front seat stitching failure**: Both seats need restitching; non-electric seats make removal simpler
- **Failing clear coat**: Peeling on bonnet, roof, and rear door handle; likely requires sanding back and respraying
- **Clunky suspension**: Suspected worn bushes and sway bar components; inspection pending

---

### 🛠️ Maintenance Philosophy

- **Oil changes every 5,000 km**, never beyond **7,000 km** — owner believes this V6 diesel benefits from more frequent changes than the standard interval
- Performs all **filters and fluids** himself to control cost and quality
- Motivated partly by fear of the **known crankshaft failure issue** on these engines — frequent oil changes are his mitigation strategy

---

### 💰 Economics of DIY vs. Dealer

- With the car now worth only ~**AUD $17,000**, any major repair at a Land Rover dealer would likely be **economically unviable** relative to the car's value
- DIY is the only realistic path to keeping it roadworthy — the owner explicitly states dealer labour rates make professional repair non-viable at this depreciation level

---

### 💡 Bottom Line

This video matters as a **realistic, unvarnished case study** of Discovery 4 ownership: a capable and practical family SUV that ages into a relentless sequence of expensive, labour-intensive repairs. The core lesson is that **DIY skills are essentially mandatory** once these vehicles depreciate below ~$20,000 AUD — dealer costs make professional maintenance economically irrational. For prospective buyers, the recurring themes of air suspension, oil cooler, manifold, and throttle body failures are concrete warnings about what to budget for.